    "James W. Knox": "Now what are we to think of men who alter the Bible text to imply that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ had a trace of sin in his character and was in danger of judgment? [4] See the chapter \u201cDrinking in Moderation\u201d in the author\u2019s work The Lost Cause Series for a detailed study of this subject. [5] See \u201cThe Degeneration of the English Language\u201d in the author\u2019s work By Definition. [6] Heretical versions of the Bible have changed the word servant to \u201cminister\u201d for obvious reasons. [7] This was the case at the time of this writing. The practice may have been discontinued by the time you read this book. Cover @page {padding: 0pt; margin:0pt} body { text-align: center; padding:0pt; margin: 0pt; } The Christ-Honoring Commentary Series The Book of Titus James W. Knox The Book of Titus Copyright \u00a9 by James W. Knox All rights reserved. Printed in the United States of America. All scripture quotations are from the Authorized (King James) Version. Where portions of a verse are set forth in block capital letters, it is for the purpose of the author's emphasis and does not represent a revision of the text. Table of Contents Preface\n22. Now what are we to think of men who alter the Bible text to imply that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ had a trace of sin in his character and was in danger of judgment? [4] See the chapter \u201cDrinking in Moderation\u201d in the author\u2019s work The Lost Cause Series for a detailed study of this subject. [5] See \u201cThe Degeneration of the English Language\u201d in the author\u2019s work By Definition. [6] Heretical versions of the Bible have changed the word servant to \u201cminister\u201d for obvious reasons. [7] This was the case at the time of this writing. The practice may have been discontinued by the time you read this book. Table of Contents"
